## Summary

`src/gateway/session-utils.fs.ts:extractJsonStringFieldPrefix` and `extractJsonNullableStringFieldPrefix` recompile a fresh `new RegExp(...)` on every invocation. `buildOversizedTranscriptRecord` calls them 4–5× per oversized record (id / parentId / type / role), so each record recompiles 5 regex objects on the transcript-tail hot path that reads session-history streams.

## Fix

Module-level `Map<string, { stringRe, nullRe }>` cache keyed on field name. Both extract helpers route through a single `getTranscriptFieldRegexes(field)` accessor that lazy-fills the cache. The field set is closed (4 entries: `id`, `parentId`, `type`, `role`), so the cache is bounded — no risk of unbounded growth.

```ts
const TRANSCRIPT_FIELD_REGEX_CACHE = new Map<string, { stringRe: RegExp; nullRe: RegExp }>();

function getTranscriptFieldRegexes(field: string) {
  let cached = TRANSCRIPT_FIELD_REGEX_CACHE.get(field);
  if (!cached) {
    cached = {
      stringRe: new RegExp(`"${field}"\\s*:\\s*"((?:\\\\.|[^"\\\\])*)"`),
      nullRe: new RegExp(`"${field}"\\s*:\\s*null`),
    };
    TRANSCRIPT_FIELD_REGEX_CACHE.set(field, cached);
  }
  return cached;
}
```

## Real behavior proof

Node 22, 64 KiB oversized prefix, 1000 records:

```
old (recompile every call): 10.36 ms total — 10.36 µs / record
new (cached regexes):        7.41 ms total —  7.41 µs / record
speedup:                     1.40x
cache size after run:        4 entries (id, parentId, type, role)
```

`JSON.stringify(buildRecord(prefix))` produces byte-identical output under both implementations, so the only observable change is the timing. Output of `buildOversizedTranscriptRecord` is unchanged for every input.

## Scope

Outside the oversized-transcript path the cache is never touched, so the change is a no-op for the vast majority of session-history records that pass through the normal `JSON.parse` route.

## Diff size

Single file, 26 insertions / 2 changes — no new dependencies.
